  "prompt": "Is Hinduism monotheistic or polytheistic?",
  "response": "Hinduism is a complex faith with elements of both monotheism and polytheism, and can be described as henotheistic.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Monotheism:** The belief in one God.\n*   **Polytheism:** The belief in many gods.\n*   **Henotheism:** The belief in and worship of a single god while accepting the existence or possible existence of other deities.\n\nMany Hindus believe in one supreme being, Brahman, which is the ultimate reality. However, Brahman is understood to manifest in various forms or aspects, which are often worshipped as individual gods and goddesses (like Vishnu, Shiva, Durga, etc.). These deities are seen as different expressions or representations of the same ultimate reality.\n\nSo, while there are many gods and goddesses, they are often viewed as different facets of the same underlying divine essence. This is why Hinduism is often described as henotheistic.",
